        <name>19.2.5.4 Solving an Exact Equation Ex1</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Solve the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}({@f1@}) = {@f2@}\).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;\(y =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] \( + \dfrac{C}{{@aa@}x^2}\), for some arbitrary constant \(C\). [[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;We are given the equation \(\dfrac{\mathrm{d}}{\mathrm{d}x}({@f1@}) = {@f2@}\) which is already in exact form.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Then, integrating both sides of the equation and rearranging, we obtain 
  \[\begin{aligned} {@aa@}yx^2 &amp;amp;= \int {@bb@}x^{{@nn@}}\ \mathrm{d}x, \\
  \implies {@aa@}yx^2 &amp;amp;= \frac{{@bb@}}{{@(nn+1)@}}x^{{@nn+1@}} + C, \\
  \implies y &amp;amp;= {@bb/(aa*(nn+1))@}x^{{@nn-1@}} + \frac{C}{{@aa@}x^2}. \end{aligned}\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
